caption: Great food, reasonable price, friendly and quality service. Will definitely return.

Outstanding lunch today.  We had one of the specials, little “purses” (sacchetti) of homemade pasta with a Gorgonzola and poached pear sauce.  We had eaten this same dish in Parma, Italy, and this was just as delectable.  The filet of sole al limone was perfectly moist and had just the right hit of lemon.  Our appetizer, eggplant rollatini, was light because this chef really knows his eggplant.  We felt so pampered by the attentive, kindly service and liked the zippered, heated tent on a chilly day.  We can’t wait to be back and eat our way through the menu!

Amazing outdoor seating with heating, overhead and side cover. We keep going back for the eggplant roulade, burrata, Chianti Nero and D’avola. Here you’ll get the type of hospitality rarely found these days. The staff are exceedingly friendly and if you are lucky you’ll get to meet one of the kids who pop out and serve on occasion. If you love family owned restaurants and want to support local businesses, this is genuine as it gets. A true local gem!

I’m surprised by the recent low-star reviews. I think it’s one of the better Italian restaurants in Park Slope. We had our Holiday Party there last week w/ 12 Ppl. Great wines, antipasto (hot & cold), pasta dishes. The Salmon Encrusto & Lamb Shank were delish - that’s what most of us had. I selected the menu ahead of time so perhaps that made a difference. Topped off w/ family style dessert selection, espresso, etc. we had a great night. Our host & head waiter were spot on. Great night out on the town. We were there for 3hrs & we not hurried out. I love going there & recommend it w/o reservation (get it?)

American "Italian" recipes masquerading as authentic Italian food. It's fine if you sell yourself as an American "red sauce" kind of place, but not if you claim to be Italian. Like another reviewer stated, the sauce tasted canned, much of the food was greasy, and the dishes lacked character. Service was mediocre. Would not return.

Italian-American food. The pastas were all simple things I could make at home. The tomato sauce tasted like it was out of a can, the olive oil based pasta was somehow sticky and the calamari was the one saving grace; which to be fair, it's fried squid. The service was also bad seeing as when we ordered wine the waiter didn't even serve us a taste first. And further than that he didn't specify that no plates were set to serving size when we specifically said we were sharing everything.  At other Italian restaurants if I say I am expecting family style the waiter tells me if there is an objection such as the plate not being sized for sharing. Our waiter did no such thing. Basic food, basic drinks, feels like a tourist trap.
